# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-aurora
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In computer science, **ACID** (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) is a set of properties of database transactions intended to guarantee data validity despite errors, power failures, and other mishaps.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] For example, a transfer of funds from one bank account to another, involving multiple changes such as debiting one account and crediting another, is a single transaction.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In 1983, Andreas Reuter and Theo Härder coined the acronym *ACID*, building on earlier work by Jim Gray who named atomicity, consistency, and durability, but not isolation, when characterizing the transaction concept.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] These four properties are the major guarantees of the transaction paradigm, which has influenced many aspects of development in database systems.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] According to Gray and Reuter, the IBM Information Management System supported ACID transactions as early as 1973 (although the acronym was created later).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] BASE stands for **b**asically **a**vailable, **s**oft state, and **e**ventually consistent: the acronym highlights that BASE is opposite of ACID, like their chemical equivalents, acid and base.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] A database either leans towards ACID or BASE, but it cannot be both (according to CAP theorem).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] For example, SQL databases (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, AWS RedShift) are structured over the ACID model, while NoSQL databases (like DynamoDB or MongoDB) use the BASE architecture.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] However, some NoSQL databases might exhibit certain ACID traits.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Transactions are often composed of multiple statements.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Atomicity guarantees that each transaction is treated as a single "unit", which either succeeds completely or fails completely: if any of the statements constituting a transaction fails to complete, the entire transaction fails and the database is left unchanged.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] An atomic system must guarantee atomicity in each and every situation, including power failures, errors, and crashes.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] A guarantee of atomicity prevents updates to the database from occurring only partially, which can cause greater problems than rejecting the whole series outright.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] As a consequence, the transaction cannot be observed to be in progress by another database client.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] At one moment in time, it has not yet happened, and at the next, it has already occurred in whole (or nothing happened if the transaction was cancelled in progress).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Consistency ensures that a transaction can only bring the database from one consistent state to another, preserving database invariants: any data written to the database must be valid according to all defined rules, including constraints, cascades, triggers, and any combination thereof.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] This prevents database corruption by an illegal transaction.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] An example of a database invariant is referential integrity, which guarantees the primary key–foreign key relationship.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Transactions are often executed concurrently (e.g., multiple transactions reading and writing to a table at the same time).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Isolation ensures that concurrent execution of transactions leaves the database in the same state that would have been obtained if the transactions were executed sequentially.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Isolation is the main goal of concurrency control; depending on the isolation level used, the effects of an incomplete transaction might not be visible to other transactions.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Durability guarantees that once a transaction has been committed, it will remain committed even in the case of a system failure (e.g., power outage or crash).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] This usually means that completed transactions (or their effects) are recorded in non-volatile memory.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] The following examples further illustrate the ACID properties.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In these examples, the database table has two columns, A and B.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] An integrity constraint requires that the value in A and the value in B must sum to 100.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Atomicity is the guarantee that series of database operations in an atomic transaction will either all occur (a successful operation), or none will occur (an unsuccessful operation).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] The series of operations cannot be separated with only some of them being executed, which makes the series of operations "indivisible".
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In other words, atomicity means indivisibility and irreducibility.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Alternatively, we may say that a logical transaction may be composed of several physical transactions.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Unless and until all component physical transactions are executed, the logical transaction will not have occurred.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] An example of an atomic transaction is a monetary transfer from bank account A to account B.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] It consists of two operations, withdrawing the money from account A and depositing it to account B.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] We would not want to see the amount removed from account A before we are sure it has also been transferred into account B.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Performing these operations in an atomic transaction ensures that the database remains in a consistent state, that is, money is neither debited nor credited if either of those two operations fails.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Consistency is a very general term, which demands that the data must meet all validation rules.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In the previous example, the validation is a requirement that *A* + *B* = 100.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] All validation rules must be checked to ensure consistency.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Assume that a transaction attempts to subtract 10 from *A* without altering *B*.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Because consistency is checked after each transaction, it is known that *A* + *B* = 100 before the transaction begins.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] If the transaction removes 10 from *A* successfully, atomicity will be achieved.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] However, a validation check will show that *A* + *B* = 90, which is inconsistent with the rules of the database.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] The entire transaction must be canceled and the affected rows rolled back to their pre-transaction state.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] If there had been other constraints, triggers, or cascades, every single change operation would have been checked in the same way as above before the transaction was committed.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Similar issues may arise with other constraints.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] We may have required the data types of both *A* and *B* to be integers.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] If we were then to enter, say, the value 13.5 for *A*, the transaction will be canceled, or the system may give rise to an alert in the form of a trigger (if/when the trigger has been written to this effect).
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Another example would be integrity constraints, which would not allow us to delete a row in one table whose primary key is referred to by at least one foreign key in other tables.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] To demonstrate isolation, we assume two transactions execute at the same time, each attempting to modify the same data.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] One of the two must wait until the other completes in order to maintain isolation.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] If these operations are performed in order, isolation is maintained, although T2 must wait.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Consider what happens if T1 fails halfway through.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] The database eliminates T1's effects, and T2 sees only valid data.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Again, consider what happens if T1 fails while modifying B in Step 4.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] By the time T1 fails, T2 has already modified A; it cannot be restored to the value it had before T1 without leaving an invalid database.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] This is known as a write-write contention, because two transactions attempted to write to the same data field.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In a typical system, the problem would be resolved by reverting to the last known good state, canceling the failed transaction T1, and restarting the interrupted transaction T2 from the good state.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Consider a transaction that transfers 10 from A to B.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] First, it removes 10 from A, then it adds 10 to B.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] At this point, the user is told the transaction was a success.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] However, the changes are still queued in the disk buffer waiting to be committed to disk.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Power fails and the changes are lost, but the user assumes (understandably) that the changes persist.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Processing a transaction often requires a sequence of operations that is subject to failure for a number of reasons.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] For instance, the system may have no room left on its disk drives, or it may have used up its allocated CPU time.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] There are two popular families of techniques: write-ahead logging and shadow paging.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In both cases, locks must be acquired on all information to be updated, and depending on the level of isolation, possibly on all data that may be read as well.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In write ahead logging, durability is guaranteed by writing the prospective change to a persistent log before changing the database.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] That allows the database to return to a consistent state in the event of a crash.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] In shadowing, updates are applied to a partial copy of the database, and the new copy is activated when the transaction commits.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Many databases rely upon locking to provide ACID capabilities.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Locking means that the transaction marks the data that it accesses so that the DBMS knows not to allow other transactions to modify it until the first transaction succeeds or fails.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] The lock must always be acquired before processing data, including data that is read but not modified.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Non-trivial transactions typically require a large number of locks, resulting in substantial overhead as well as blocking other transactions.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] For example, if user A is running a transaction that has to read a row of data that user B wants to modify, user B must wait until user A's transaction completes.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Two-phase locking is often applied to guarantee full isolation.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] An alternative to locking is multiversion concurrency control, in which the database provides each reading transaction the prior, unmodified version of data that is being modified by another active transaction.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] This allows readers to operate without acquiring locks, i.e., writing transactions do not block reading transactions, and readers do not block writers.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Going back to the example, when user A's transaction requests data that user B is modifying, the database provides A with the version of that data that existed when user B started his transaction.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] User A gets a consistent view of the database even if other users are changing data.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] One implementation, namely snapshot isolation, relaxes the isolation property.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Guaranteeing ACID properties in a distributed transaction across a distributed database, where no single node is responsible for all data affecting a transaction, presents additional complications.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Network connections might fail, or one node might successfully complete its part of the transaction and then be required to roll back its changes because of a failure on another node.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] The two-phase commit protocol (not to be confused with two-phase locking) provides atomicity for distributed transactions to ensure that each participant in the transaction agrees on whether the transaction should be committed or not.
[src:aws-aurora/acid] Briefly, in the first phase, one node (the coordinator) interrogates the other nodes (the participants), and only when all reply that they are prepared does the coordinator, in the second phase, formalize the transaction.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] Aurora offered MySQL compatible service upon its release in 2014.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] It added PostgreSQL compatibility in October 2017.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] In August 2017, Aurora Fast Cloning (copy-on-write) feature was added allowing customers to create copies of their databases.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] In May 2018, Aurora Backtrack was added which allows developers to rewind database clusters without creating a new one.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] It became possible to stop and start Aurora Clusters in September 2018.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] In August 2018, Amazon began to offer a serverless version.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] In 2019 the developers of Aurora won the SIGMOD Systems Award for fundamentally redesigning relational database storage for cloud environments.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] Aurora automatically allocates database storage space in 10-gigabyte increments, as needed, up to a maximum of 128 terabytes.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] Aurora offers automatic, six-way replication of those chunks across three availability zones for improved availability and fault-tolerance.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] Aurora provides users with performance metrics, such as query throughput and latency.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] Aurora Multi-Master allows creation of multiple read-write instances in an Aurora database across multiple availability zones, which enables uptime-sensitive applications to achieve continuous write availability through instance failure.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] Amazon designed Aurora to be compatible with MySQL, meaning that tools for querying or managing MySQL databases (such as the mysql command-line client and the MySQL Workbench graphical user-interface) can be used.
[src:aws-aurora/amazon-aurora] As of December 2021, Amazon Aurora is compatible with MySQL 5.6, 5.7, and 8.0.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:aws-aurora/database-replication] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL is free and open-source software under the terms of the GNU General Public License, and is also available under a variety of proprietary licenses.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL was owned and sponsored by the Swedish company MySQL AB, which was bought by Sun Microsystems (now Oracle Corporation).
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In 2010, when Oracle acquired Sun, Widenius forked the open-source MySQL project to create MariaDB.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL has stand-alone clients that allow users to interact directly with a MySQL database using SQL, but more often, MySQL is used with other programs to implement applications that need relational database capability.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL is a component of the LAMP web application software stack (and others), which is an acronym for *Linux, Apache, MySQL, Perl/PHP/Python*.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL is used by many database-driven web applications, including Drupal, Joomla, phpBB, and WordPress.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL is also used by many popular websites, including Facebook, Flickr, MediaWiki, Twitter, and YouTube.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Its SQL parser is written in yacc, but it uses a home-brewed lexical analyzer.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL works on many system platforms, including AIX, BSDi, FreeBSD, HP-UX, ArcaOS, eComStation, IBM i, IRIX, Linux, macOS, Microsoft Windows, NetBSD, Novell NetWare, OpenBSD, OpenSolaris, OS/2 Warp, QNX, Oracle Solaris, Symbian, SunOS, SCO OpenServer, SCO UnixWare, Sanos and Tru64.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The MySQL server software itself and the client libraries use dual-licensing distribution.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] They are offered under GPL version 2, or a proprietary license.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Support can be obtained from the official manual.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Free support additionally is available in different IRC channels and forums.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Oracle offers paid support via its MySQL Enterprise products.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] They differ in the scope of services and in price.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Additionally, a number of third party organisations exist to provide support and services.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL has received positive reviews, and reviewers noticed it "performs extremely well in the average case" and that the "developer interfaces are there, and the documentation (not to mention feedback in the real world via Web sites and the like) is very, very good".
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It has also been tested to be a "fast, stable and true multi-user, multi-threaded SQL database server".
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL was created by a Swedish company, MySQL AB, founded by Swedes David Axmark and Allan Larsson, along with Finn Michael "Monty" Widenius.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Original development of MySQL by Widenius and Axmark began in 1994.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The first version of MySQL appeared on 23 May 1995.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It was initially created for personal usage from mSQL based on the low-level language ISAM, which the creators considered too slow and inflexible.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] They created a new SQL interface, while keeping the same API as mSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] By keeping the API consistent with the mSQL system, many developers were able to use MySQL instead of the (proprietarily licensed) mSQL antecedent.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Work on version 6 stopped after the Sun Microsystems acquisition.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The MySQL Cluster product uses version 7.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The decision was made to jump to version 8 as the next major version number.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] On 15 June 2001, NuSphere sued MySQL AB, TcX DataKonsult AB and its original authors Michael ("Monty") Widenius and David Axmark in U.S.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] District Court in Boston for "breach of contract, tortious interference with third party contracts and relationships and unfair competition".
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In 2002, MySQL AB sued Progress NuSphere for copyright and trademark infringement in United States district court.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] NuSphere had allegedly violated MySQL AB's copyright by linking MySQL's GPL'ed code with NuSphere Gemini table without being in compliance with the license.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] After a preliminary hearing before Judge Patti Saris on 27 February 2002, the parties entered settlement talks and eventually settled.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In October 2005, Oracle Corporation acquired Innobase OY, the Finnish company that developed the third-party InnoDB storage engine that allows MySQL to provide such functionality as transactions and foreign keys.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] After the acquisition, an Oracle press release mentioned that the contracts that make the company's software available to MySQL AB would be due for renewal (and presumably renegotiation) some time in 2006.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] During the MySQL Users Conference in April 2006, MySQL AB issued a press release that confirmed that MySQL AB and Innobase OY agreed to a "multi-year" extension of their licensing agreement.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In February 2006, Oracle Corporation acquired Sleepycat Software, makers of the Berkeley DB, a database engine providing the basis for another MySQL storage engine.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] This had little effect, as Berkeley DB was not widely used, and was dropped (due to lack of use) in MySQL 5.1.12, a pre-GA release of MySQL 5.1 released in October 2006.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In January 2008, Sun Microsystems bought MySQL AB for $1 billion.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In April 2009, Oracle Corporation entered into an agreement to purchase Sun Microsystems, then owners of MySQL copyright and trademark.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Sun's board of directors unanimously approved the deal.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It was also approved by Sun's shareholders, and by the U.S. government on 20 August 2009.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] On 14 December 2009, Oracle pledged to continue to enhance MySQL as it had done for the previous four years.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] A movement against Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB, to "Save MySQL" from Oracle was started by one of the MySQL AB founders, Monty Widenius.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The petition of 50,000+ developers and users called upon the European Commission to block approval of the acquisition.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] At the same time, some Free Software opinion leaders (including Pamela Jones of Groklaw, Jan Wildeboer and Carlo Piana, who also acted as co-counsel in the merger regulation procedure) advocated for the unconditional approval of the merger.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] As part of the negotiations with the European Commission, Oracle committed that MySQL server will continue until at least 2015 to use the dual-licensing strategy long used by MySQL AB, with proprietary and GPL versions available.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The antitrust of the EU had been "pressuring it to divest MySQL as a condition for approval of the merger".
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] But the US Department of Justice, at the request of Oracle, pressured the EU to approve the merger unconditionally.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The European Commission eventually unconditionally approved Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB on 21 January 2010.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In January 2010, before Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB, Monty Widenius started a GPL-only fork, MariaDB.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MariaDB is based on the same code base as MySQL server 5.5 and aims to maintain compatibility with Oracle-provided versions.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL is offered under two different editions: the open source MySQL Community Server and the proprietary Enterprise Server.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL Enterprise Server is differentiated by a series of proprietary extensions which install as server plugins, but otherwise shares the version numbering system and is built from the same code base.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The developers release minor updates of the MySQL Server approximately every two months.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The sources can be obtained from MySQL's website or from MySQL's GitHub repository, both under the GPL license.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] When using some storage engines other than the default of InnoDB, MySQL does not comply with the full SQL standard for some of the implemented functionality, including foreign key references.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Check constraints are parsed but ignored by all storage engines before MySQL version 8.0.15.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Up until MySQL 5.7, triggers are limited to one per action / timing, meaning that at most one trigger can be defined to be executed after an INSERT operation, and one before INSERT on the same table.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Before MySQL 8.0.28, inbuilt functions like UNIX_TIMESTAMP() would return 0 after 03:14:07 UTC on 19 January 2038.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In 2017, an attempt to solve the problem was submitted, but was not used for the final solution that was shipped in 2022.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL can be built and installed manually from source code, but it is more commonly installed from a binary package unless special customizations are required.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] On most Linux distributions, the package management system can download and install MySQL with minimal effort, though further configuration is often required to adjust security and optimization settings.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Though MySQL began as a low-end alternative to more powerful proprietary databases, it has gradually evolved to support higher-scale needs as well.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It is still most commonly used in small to medium scale single-server deployments, either as a component in a LAMP-based web application or as a standalone database server.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Much of MySQL's appeal originates in its relative simplicity and ease of use, which is enabled by an ecosystem of open source tools such as phpMyAdmin.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In the medium range, MySQL can be scaled by deploying it on more powerful hardware, such as a multi-processor server with gigabytes of memory.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] There are, however, limits to how far performance can scale on a single server ('scaling up'), so on larger scales, multi-server MySQL ('scaling out') deployments are required to provide improved performance and reliability.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] A typical high-end configuration can include a powerful source database (formerly known as master database) which handles data write operations and is replicated to multiple replicas (formerly known as slaves) that handle all read operations.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The source server continually pushes binlog events to connected replicas so in the event of failure a replica can be promoted to become the new source, minimizing downtime.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Further improvements in performance can be achieved by caching the results from database queries in memory using memcached, or breaking down a database into smaller chunks called shards which can be spread across a number of distributed server clusters.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Oracle MySQL offers a high availability solution with a mix of tools including the MySQL router and the MySQL shell.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] They are based on Group Replication, open source tools.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MariaDB offers a similar offer in terms of products.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL can also be run on cloud computing platforms such as Microsoft Azure, Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud, and Oracle Cloud Infrastructure.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In this implementation, cloud users can upload a machine image of their own with MySQL installed, or use a ready-made machine image with an optimized installation of MySQL on it, such as the one provided by Amazon EC2.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Some cloud platforms offer MySQL "as a service".
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In this configuration, application owners do not have to install and maintain the MySQL database on their own.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Instead, the database service provider takes responsibility for installing and maintaining the database, and application owners pay according to their usage.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Notable cloud-based MySQL services are the Amazon Relational Database Service; Oracle MySQL HeatWave Database Service, Azure Database for MySQL, Rackspace; HP Converged Cloud; Heroku and Jelastic.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In this model the database service provider takes responsibility for maintaining the host and database.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] A graphical user interface (GUI) is a type of interface that allows users to interact with electronic devices or programs through graphical icons and visual indicators such as secondary notation, as opposed to text-based interfaces, typed command labels or text navigation.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Third-party proprietary and free graphical administration applications (or "front ends") are available that integrate with MySQL and enable users to work with database structure and data visually.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL Workbench is the integrated environment for MySQL.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It was developed by MySQL AB, and enables users to graphically administer MySQL databases and visually design database structures.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL Workbench is available in three editions, the regular free and open source *Community Edition* which may be downloaded from the MySQL website, and the proprietary *Standard Edition* which extends and improves the feature set of the Community Edition, and the MySQL Cluster CGE.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] A command-line interface is a means of interacting with a computer program where the user issues commands to the program by typing in successive lines of text (command lines).
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL ships with many command line tools, from which the main interface is the mysql client.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL Utilities is a set of utilities designed to perform common maintenance and administrative tasks.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Originally included as part of the MySQL Workbench, the utilities are a stand-alone download available from Oracle.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Percona Toolkit is a cross-platform toolkit for MySQL, developed in Perl.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Percona Toolkit can be used to prove replication is working correctly, fix corrupted data, automate repetitive tasks, and speed up servers.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Percona Toolkit is included with several Linux distributions such as CentOS and Debian, and packages are available for Fedora and Ubuntu as well.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Percona Toolkit was originally developed as Maatkit, but as of late 2011, Maatkit is no longer developed.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL shell is a tool for interactive use and administration of the MySQL database.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It supports JavaScript, Python or SQL modes and it can be used for administration and access purposes.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Many programming languages with language-specific APIs include libraries for accessing MySQL databases.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] These include MySQL Connector/Net for .NET/CLI Languages, and the JDBC driver for Java.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MySQL offers Connector/C++ for interfacing with C++ in namespace `mysqlx`.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] In addition, an ODBC interface called MySQL Connector/ODBC allows additional programming languages that support the ODBC interface to communicate with a MySQL database, such as ASP or ColdFusion.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The HTSQL – URL-based query method also ships with a MySQL adapter, allowing direct interaction between a MySQL database and any web client via structured URLs.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Other drivers exists for languages like Python or Node.js.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] MariaDB is a community-developed fork of the MySQL relational database management system intended to remain free under the GNU GPL.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The fork has been led by the original developers of MySQL, who forked it due to concerns over its acquisition by Oracle.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Percona Server for MySQL, forked by Percona, aims to retain close compatibility to the official MySQL releases.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Also included in Percona Server for MySQL is XtraDB, Percona's fork of the InnoDB Storage Engine.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Drizzle was a free software/open source relational database management system (DBMS) that was forked from the now-defunct 6.0 development branch of the MySQL DBMS.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Like MySQL, Drizzle had a client/server architecture and uses SQL as its primary command language.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Drizzle was distributed under version 2 and 3 of the GNU General Public License (GPL) with portions, including the protocol drivers and replication messaging under the BSD license.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Thus, WebScaleSQL opened a path toward deduplicating the efforts each company had been putting into maintaining its own branch of MySQL, and toward bringing together more developers.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] By combining the efforts of these companies and incorporating various changes and new features into MySQL, WebScaleSQL aimed at supporting the deployment of MySQL in large-scale environments.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The project's source code is licensed under version 2 of the GNU General Public License, and is hosted on GitHub.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] The OurDelta distribution, created by the Australian company Open Query (later acquired by Catalyst IT Australia), had two versions: 5.0, which was based on MySQL, and 5.1, which was based on MariaDB.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] It included patches developed by Open Query and by other notable members of the MySQL community including Jeremy Cole and Google.
[src:aws-aurora/mysql] Once the patches were incorporated into the MariaDB mainline, OurDelta's objectives were achieved and OurDelta passed on its build and packaging toolchain to Monty Program (now MariaDB Plc).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-aurora/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:aws-aurora/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
